         b'\n\t\t<div class="post-116 post type-post status-publish format-sta'
         b'ndard hentry category-education category-event category-sociology ca'
         b'tegory-talk" id="post-116">\n\t\t\t<h2>A Hunger for Books (Not Blogs'
         b')</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p>I was recently rea'
         b'ding Dorris Lessing&#8217;s Nobel Prize for Literature acceptance sp'
         b'eech (full text <a href="http://books.guardian.co.uk/review/story/0,'
         b',2223780,00.html" target="_blank">here</a>). It&#8217;s an excellent'
         b' read, a story of storytelling, that recalls her experiences in Afri'
         b'ca and the influence of books on a writer. I strongly recommend all '
         b'to read it. However, as inspirational as it is, there is also a stro'
         b'ng feeling of cynicism towards the culture heralded on by the techno'
         b'logy revolution, and some points worth thinking about. Here is a sho'
         b'rt quote:</p>\n<blockquote><p>&#8220;We are in a fragmenting cult'
         b'ure, where our certainties of even a few decades ago are questioned '
         b'and where it is common for young men and women, who have had years o'
         b'f education, to know nothing of the world, to have read nothing, kno'
         b'wing only some speciality or other, for instance, computers.</p>'
         b'\n<p>What has happened to us is an amazing invention &#8211; comp'
         b'uters and the internet and TV. It is a revolution. This is not the f'
         b'irst revolution the human race has dealt with. The printing revoluti'
         b'on, which did not take place in a matter of a few decades, but took '
         b'much longer, transformed our minds and ways of thinking. A foolhardy'
         b' lot, we accepted it all, as we always do, never asked: &#8220;What '
         b'is going to happen to us now, with this invention of print?&#8221; I'
         b'n the same way, we never thought to ask, &#8220;How will our lives, '
         b'our way of thinking, be changed by the internet, which has seduced a'
         b' whole generation with its inanities so that even quite reasonable p'
         b'eople will confess that, once they are hooked, it is hard to cut fre'
         b'e, and they may find a whole day has passed in blogging etc?&#8221;<'
         b'/p></blockquote>\n<p>I found it strange how she describes the pri'
         b'nting revolution as something good, by allowing &#8220;voices unhear'
         b'd&#8221; to wield their talent, but the internet revolution as somet'
         b'hing meaningless, fragmenting, and wasteful. It seems to either impl'
         b'y that publishers have been given the divine gift of knowing what is'
         b' good to publish, or that people (are dumb, and) lack the collective'
         b' knowledge to find what is worth reading. Is there no such thing as '
         b'<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Collective_unconscious">collec'
         b'tive wisdom</a>? Does a change of medium naturally imply a change in'
         b' content and quality? Perhaps her words reflect <a href="http://en.w'
         b'ikipedia.org/wiki/Future_Shock">Toffler&#8217;s predictions</a>, or '
         b'it is impossible for her to find any quality in the chaotic communit'
         b'y that we call the web?</p>\n<p>After all, her message came to me'
         b' by means of blogs and online news. Any thoughts?</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t'
