         b'#comment-1525">\n\t\t\tDecember 19, 2007 at 5:32 pm</a>\t\t</div>\n'
         b'\n\t\t<p>The parallel divisions between print/internet and white/bl'
         b'ack are revealing &#8211; future shock as a species of orientalism? '
         b'Why didn&#8217;t the oral cultures of precolonial Africa become writ'
         b'ten cultures? Perhaps because the books were imported but the presse'
         b's were not &#8211; the colonists imported their own cultures when th'
         b'ey imported their own books. I wonder what Lessing thinks of the One'
         b' Laptop Per Child project.</p>\n<p>If half the children in a Lond'
         b'on school have never read a novel, does that mean literature is dyin'
         b'g? How many people in Shakespearean England could read? Or in coloni'
         b'al Africa, when Shakespeare was being taught to African children in '
         b'&#8220;the mission schools, the better schools&#8221;?</p>\n<p>I '
         b'doubt that someone who refers to &#8220;computers and the internet a'
         b'nd TV&#8221; as a single invention has really explored them in depth'
         b', but even if Lessing&#8217;s criticism of &#8220;the internet, whic'
         b'h has seduced a whole generation with its inanities&#8221; amounts t'
         b'o more than future shock, we might ask who stands to gain from a &#8'
         b'220;fragmenting culture&#8221; and who stands to lose.</p>\n\n\t\t<d'
         b'iv class="reply">\n\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</li><!--'
